1️⃣ Hibernate Performance (Overview)

Hibernate performance mainly depends on how efficiently data is fetched from the database. Most performance problems are caused by:

✅ Too many SQL queries
✅ Fetching unnecessary data
✅ Improper relationships mapping
✅ Wrong fetch strategies
✅ Missing caching

Common Performance Bottlenecks

N+1 Select Problem (most common)

LazyInitializationException misuse

Fetching large object graphs unintentionally

No batching or pagination

Excessive joins

Hibernate performance tuning is mostly about controlling database access, not Java execution speed.

2️⃣ The N+1 Select Problem (Very Important)
What is N+1?

The N+1 problem happens when Hibernate executes:

1 query to fetch parent records

N additional queries to fetch child records (one per parent)

Example
Entity Relationship
class Department {
    @OneToMany(mappedBy="department")
    List<Employee> employees;
}

What You Expect (Ideal)
SELECT * FROM department;
SELECT * FROM employee WHERE department_id IN (...);


👉 Only 2 queries

What Actually Happens (N+1)
SELECT * FROM department;   -- 1 query

SELECT * FROM employee WHERE department_id=1;
SELECT * FROM employee WHERE department_id=2;
SELECT * FROM employee WHERE department_id=3;
...


👉 1 + N queries

If N = 100 → 101 queries 😱

Why It Happens

Because Hibernate loads associations lazily by default (especially collections).

When you access:

department.getEmployees()


Hibernate fires a new query for each department.

Why It's Dangerous

Massive DB load

Slow APIs

High latency

Hidden until production scale

✅ Solutions to N+1
1. JOIN FETCH (Best Fix)
SELECT d FROM Department d
JOIN FETCH d.employees


Hibernate generates:

SELECT * FROM department
JOIN employee ON ...


✔ Single query

2. Entity Graph
@EntityGraph(attributePaths = "employees")
List<Department> findAll();


Cleaner for Spring Data JPA.
5. Batch Fetching (Huge Performance Boost)

When loading multiple lazy collections → Hibernate can batch.

application.properties
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.default_batch_fetch_size=20
3. Batch Fetching
hibernate.default_batch_fetch_size=20


Hibernate loads children in groups instead of one-by-one.

4. DTO Projection (Highly Efficient)

Fetch only required fields.

3️⃣ Fetch Types in Hibernate

Fetch type controls WHEN related data is loaded.

There are two main types:

✅ FetchType.LAZY (Default for Collections)
Meaning:

Data is loaded only when accessed.

@OneToMany(fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
List<Employee> employees;

Behavior
Department dept = repo.findById(1);


SQL executed:

SELECT * FROM department WHERE id=1;


Employees NOT loaded yet.

Only when:

dept.getEmployees();


Another query runs.

✅ Advantages

Better performance

Loads only needed data

Memory efficient

❌ Risk

LazyInitializationException if session is closed.

✅ FetchType.EAGER (Default for ManyToOne)
Meaning:

Data loads immediately with parent.

@ManyToOne(fetch = FetchType.EAGER)
Department department;


Query:

SELECT * FROM employee
LEFT JOIN department ...

❌ Problems with EAGER

Loads unnecessary data

Creates huge joins

Causes hidden N+1 issues

Hard to control queries

👉 Senior Hibernate rule:

✅ Avoid EAGER unless absolutely required

4️⃣ LAZY vs EAGER (Quick Comparison)
Feature	LAZY	EAGER
Load Time	On demand	Immediately
Performance	Better	Often worse
Memory Usage	Low	High
Query Control	High	Low
Recommended	✅ Yes	❌ Rarely
5️⃣ Best Practices (Real-World)
⭐ Golden Rules

Prefer LAZY everywhere.

Use JOIN FETCH when needed.

Never rely on default fetching blindly.

Use DTO projections for APIs.

Monitor SQL logs:

spring.jpa.show-sql=true


Measure query count during testing.

6️⃣ How Everything Connects
Fetch Type → Determines loading strategy
        ↓
Lazy Loading → Can cause N+1
        ↓
JOIN FETCH / Batch → Fix performance


Hibernate performance tuning = controlling fetching behavior.

